===Etymology===
{{PIE word|en|ḱóm}}
From {{inh|en|enm|yclept}}, {{m|enm|ycleped}}, {{m|enm|iclept}}{{nb...|clēped, clept, icleped, iclepyd, icliped, iclipet, icluped, yclepid, yclepud, ycluped, ȝecleped|otherforms=1}} ({{m|enm|i-}}, {{m|enm|y-|pos={{glossary|prefix}} forming {{glossary|past}} {{glossary|participle}}s}}<ref>{{R:MED Online|entry=i-|pos=pref|id=MED21576}}</ref> + {{m|enm|clepen|t=to say, speak, utter; to call, shout; to name; to address; to appeal to, beg, pray; to ask, request; to appear; to send for, summon; to convene; to call forth, induce; to lay claim}}<ref>{{R:MED Online|entry=clēpen|pos=v|id=MED7971}}</ref> + {{m|enm|-ed}}, {{m|enm|-t|pos={{glossary|suffix}} forming past participles of {{glossary|weak verb}}s}}),<ref>{{R:MED Online|entry=-(e)d|pos=''suf.''(2)|noformat=1|id=MED12958}}</ref> from {{inh|en|ang|ġeclypod}}, {{m|ang|ġeclipod}} ({{m|ang|ġe-|pos=suffix forming past participles or participle {{glossary|adjective}}s}} + {{m|ang|clypian}}, {{m|ang|clipian|t=to call out, cry; to appeal}} {{qualifier|West Saxon}}{{nb...|(Anglian) cleopian, cliopian|otherforms=1}} + {{m|ang|-d|pos=suffix forming past participles}}).<ref>Compare {{R:OED Online|entry=yclept {{!}} ycleped|pos=adj|id=231389|date=December 2020|nodot=1}}; {{R:Lexico|pos=adj}}</ref> {{m|ang||Clipian}} is derived from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*klipjaną}}, {{m|gem-pro|*klapjaną|t=to be noisy; to chatter}}, probably related to {{m|gem-pro|*klappōną|t=to clap, pound, or strike (especially two things against each other); to make loud noises, especially breathing or pulsating; to chatter}}, and ultimately {{glossary|onomatopoeic}}. {{doublet|en|clap}}.
